Title: and other problems from Optical Mapping  
Author: Laxmi Parida 
Address: New York University, USA.  
Affiliation: Department of Computer Science, Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences,  
Note: Inapproximability of Flip-Cut, Shift-Cut  
Abstract: Courant Inst. of Math. Sciences Technical report, TR1997-740, August 1997. (Also submitted for journal publication) Abstract Optical Mapping is a single molecule approach capable of constructing ordered restriction maps of DNA molecules and raises many interesting computational problems. Some computational complexity aspects of a these problems have been addressed previously [AMS97, DHM97, MP96], but it had remained unresolved if they yield to polynomial time approximation schemes. In this paper we resolve most of these open problems (such as BFC [GP96, MP96], pairwise match [AMS97, Ree97] problems and others) and also improve on earlier results on other problems [AMS97, DHM97]. We show that all the problems, with only one exception, are MAX SNP-hard. This implies that obtaining an * approximation for a problem, where * &gt; * 0 , for some fixed * 0 (depending on the problem) is also NP hard. Further, we obtain theoretical upper bounds on the polynomial time approximation factors for all of the above problems that are hard. (See Table 1 for a summary of the results.) The proof technique uses a gap-preserving reduction of an instance of a graph problem to these problems. We believe that our results would give insight to computational biologists in designing better heuristics for the problems, and to biochemists in understanding the trade-offs among the various error sources. Since similar problems are likely to arise in other single molecule methods as well, we believe that the study of these problems would be of interest to a larger group of biochemists, molecular biologists and others.
