Reference-contexts: Large scale construction of ordered restriction maps for eukaryotic chromosomes is laborious and difficult, in part because traditional approaches to molecular analysis were designed to analyze genes rather than genomes. A single molecule approach called Optical Mapping <ref> [WHS95, Men+95, Sch+93] </ref> is a new approach for the rapid production of ordered restriction maps. Optical Mapping fixes elongated DNA molecules onto surfaces by electrostatic interactions. The fixation conditions are carefully controlled in order to allow enzymatic reactions on the surface. The restriction sites are detected by flourescence microscopy.
